@page tutorial Tutorial

# Tutorial: Lazer Assault
This page showcases the engine with a tutorial for a simple lazer obstacle game.

@remark This page is incomplete while the engine is in development. Come back soon!

## Game Overview

* %Player can move around in a terminal sized world
* Vertical and horizontal lazers appear, damaging the player
* Lazers flicker twice before firing to allow player time to dodge
* Game is over when player health reaches 0
* Score is tracked by each wave avoided
* Score is displayed on screen
* Health is displayed on screen

## Part 1. Setting up `main()`
We use the template main function to initialize the engine with base specifications.

* World size restricted
* Gravity settings changed
* Player spawn set
```cpp
int main()
{
    /// ENGINE SETUP
    PotatoEngine& engine = PotatoEngine::Get();
    engine.LoadSubobjects();
    GameInstance* instance = GameInstance::get();
    
    // ENGINE SETTINGS
    instance->MS_REPEAT_THRESHOLD = 195;
    instance->FRAMES_PER_SECOND = 60.f;

    /// LEVEL SETUP
    [[maybe_unused]] World* world = instance->GetWorld();
    PersistentLevel level("save1.json"); // default save
    level.LoadStaticActors();

    /// WORLD SETTINGS
    world->Settings.Size = Vector2(80,24); // restrict level size
    world->Settings.doGravity = false;

    /// PLAYER SETUP
    PlayerController* playerController = instance->GetPlayerController();
    Player* player = playerController->GetPlayer();
    player->SetPosition(Vector2(40,12)); // player spawns in the middle of world

    player->Texture = 'P';

    /// UI SETUP
    [[maybe_unused]] IHUDController* HUDController = engine.GetHUDController();
    // ScoreWidget* scoreWidget = HUDController->AddWidget<ScoreWidget>("ScoreWidget");

    /// PLAY
    engine.BeginPlay();

    engine.Resolve();
    

    return 0;
}
```

## Part 2. ScoreWidget class
We need a widget to display the player's score on screen.

`src/UI/ScoreWidget.hpp` and `src/UI/ScoreWidget.cpp` are created.

* `ScoreWidget` is declared, inheriting from `Widget`
    * Default constructor/destructor defined
    * `IncrementScore()` method declared to update player score
    * `UpdateScreen()` method declared to update the widget contents
    * `Score` variable declared
```cpp
// ScoreWidget.hpp

class ScoreWidget : public Widget
{
public:
    ScoreWidget(std::string UID);
    virtual ~ScoreWidget() noexcept = default;

    void IncrementScore();
private:
    int Score;

    void UpdateScreen();
};
```
Our constructor must call the parent constructor to instantiate properly. Score is default-initialized. A `TextElement` is added to the widget to display the score text, and its settings are updated.

`IncrementScore()` should be called every time there a wave completes. We will setup an event binding later.
```cpp
// GameManager.cpp

ScoreWidget::ScoreWidget(std::string UID) : Widget(UID) {
    Score = 0;

    TextElement* scoreDisplay = AddElement<TextElement>("scoreDisplay");
    scoreDisplay->SetScreenPosition(Vector2(0,0));
    scoreDisplay->SetScreenSize(Vector2(10,1));
    scoreDisplay->field = "Score: .";
    scoreDisplay->SetVisibility(true);

}
```
The `IncrementScore()` method increments and immediately updates the screen.
```cpp
// GameManager.cpp

void ScoreWidget::IncrementScore() {
    ++Score;
    UpdateScreen();
}
```
The `UpdateScreen()` method gets the display element by name and updates its field
```cpp
// GameManager.cpp

void ScoreWidget::UpdateScreen() {
    TextElement* scoreDisplay = dynamic_cast<TextElement*>(GetElement("scoreDisplay"));
    scoreDisplay->field = "Score: " + std::to_string(Score);
}
```

